\section*{First paragraph}

\textbf{The partitioning of biomass in terrestrial vegetation between leaves, stems and roots is a critical component of dynamic global vegetation models (DGVMs). Biomass partioning is consistently shown to be one of the most uncertain and important drivers for global predictions of carbon storage \cite{ise_comparison_2010}, the lifetime of carbon in ecosystems \cite{friend_carbon_2014}, and the CO$_2$ response of net primary production \cite{dekauwe2014does} . Little is known about direct and indirect effects of climate on biomass partitioning, largely due to the lack of a global individual-based biomass dataset. Here, we analyze the largest database on plant biomass to date [cite]. We show that partitioning of biomass to leaves vs. woody stems is strongly dependent on the plant functional type. Evergreen gymnosperms maintain three times more leaf biomass at a given total aboveground biomass than deciduous angiosperms, with evergreen angiosperms taking an intermediate value. We found that leaf mass per area, an indicator of leaf construction cost, explains these differences so that the PFTs converged in the ratio  of leaf area to aboveground biomass. We found weak effects of climate while accounting for PFT effects, suggesting that climate-related differences are captured largely by a shift in PFT. These results can be used to constrain biomass partitioning routines in global dynamic vegetation models.}


