\section*{Methods}

We used the recently compiled Biomass And Allometry Database (BAAD) (Falster et al., in review), including a total of \Sexpr{nrow(baad$data)} observations, but here we use only data that include leaf mass ($M_F$), leaf area ($A_F$), aboveground woody biomass ($M_W$), total root biomass ($M_R$), plant height ($H$), and stem area measured at ground level ($A_S$), or at breast height (ca. 1.3m) ($A_{Sbh}$).  For each analysis, we therefore used different subsets of the data (far fewer observations are available for root biomass, in particular). Sample sizes by PFT are summarized in Tables~\ref{table:count1}-\ref{table:count4} We exluded glasshouse and common garden studies, including only field grown woody plants (including plantations). We considered three plant functional types : evergreen angiosperms, evergreen gymnosperms, and decidous angiosperms. We excluded  deciduous gymnosperms because few data were available. All locations were further separated into boreal (including sub-boreal), temperate, and tropical biomes (decided by contributing author, but checked with MAT and latitude).

For the aboveground biomass pools, we calculated the leaf mass fraction ($M_F / M_T$, where $M_T$ is total aboveground biomass) and leaf area ratio ($A_F / M_T$). LMF, LAR, LMA, $M_F$ and $A_F$ are related by,

$$LMF = M_F / M_T = (M_F / A_F) (A_F / M_T) = LMA * LAR$$

We were unable to further decompose $A_S/M_W$ into wood volume and wood density components (cf. \cite{chave_tree_2005}) because wood density data were available only for a small subset of data.
We did not include LMA estimates from another database (such as TRY), instead only used SLA directly estimated for the harvested plants (typically for a subsample of leaves). For conifers, leaf area was converted to half-total surface area, which is most appropriate in terms of light interception  \cite{lang_application_1991, chen_defining_1992}, for comparison to flat leaves.

Stem cross-sectional area was measured either at breast height (ca. 1.3m) and/or at the base of the plant. For the subset of the data where both were measured, we estimated basal stem area ($A_S$) from breast height stem area ($A_{Sbh}$) using non-linear regression (see~SIXXX). The main results were similar when we repeated it for data where either $A_S$ or $A_{Sbh}$ were directly measured (not shown).

We used a generalized additive model (GAM) to visualize the relationships, but these were not used for formal inference. Instead we used linear mixed-effects models (with species within study as the random effect) to test for significance and to calculate confidence intervals for PFT-specific averages. Least-square means for LMF and LAR were calculated with the 'lsmeans' package in R. All variables were log-transformed prior to analysis. Variance partitioning with marginal (fixed effects) and conditional (fixed and random effects) $R^2$ for linear mixed-effects models as reported by \cite{nakagawa_general_2013}.
 


